Trigonometry
============


Pythagoras
----------

Pythagoras is calculated as

```latex
\sqrt[2]{a^2 + b^2}
```

so if we have

```javascript
// settings: play, hidden
module.exports = <Latex source={`a = ${exports.a}`} />
```

and

```javascript
// settings: play, hidden
module.exports = <Latex source={`b = ${exports.b}`} />;
```

our ```$$c$$``` should be

```javascript
// settings: play, hidden
exports.result = Math.sqrt(Math.pow(exports.a, 2) + Math.pow(exports.b, 2))
module.exports = <Latex source={`
  \\sqrt[2]{${exports.a}^2 + ${exports.b}^2} \\simeq ${Math.round(exports.result)}
`} />;
```

```javascript
// settings: play, hidden
const { lineWidth, a, b } = exports
const canvas = document.createElement('canvas');
canvas.height = exports.b + lineWidth * 2;
canvas.width = exports.a + lineWidth * 2;
const context = canvas.getContext('2d');
context.fillStyle = '#e67e22';
context.strokeStyle = '#000'
context.lineWidth =  lineWidth;
context.beginPath();
context.moveTo(lineWidth, b + lineWidth);
context.lineTo(a + lineWidth, b + lineWidth);
context.lineTo(a + lineWidth, lineWidth);
context.lineTo(lineWidth, b + lineWidth);
context.closePath();
context.fill();
context.stroke();

module.exports = canvas;
```

# Global Modules

Modules can be shared across documents, so it is possible to extend the tools availible.

For instance, if we create a module with to numbers and a function to multibly them.

```javascript
// settings: name=demomodule

exports.a = 10;

exports.b = 15;

exports.calculate = (a, b) => a * b;
```

...the we can access them using its name in another document.

```javascript
// settings: play
module.exports = require('demomodule').then(([demo]) => {
  return demo.calculate(demo.a, demo.b);
});
```

